The "Coeur d'Alene Basin Restoration Act of 1994" is cited in this section as the Act's short title. It also introduces the Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference under Title I of the Federal Water Pollution Control Act. The Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference is established to develop a pollution prevention and restoration plan for the basin. The conference will include representatives from the EPA, Coeur d'Alene Indian tribe, and Idaho Department of Environmental Quality. The Management Conference for the Coeur d'Alene Basin will consist of representatives from the EPA, Coeur d'Alene Indian tribe, and Idaho Department of Environmental Quality. The conference will appoint a management advisory committee, a technical advisory committee, and a citizens' advisory committee. The Management Conference for the Coeur d'Alene Basin appoints a management advisory committee, a technical advisory committee, and a citizens' advisory committee. Ex officio members include the Member of the United States House of Representatives within the congressional district of the basin. The Management Conference for the Coeur d'Alene Basin appoints ex officio members, including the Member of the US House of Representatives from the basin's congressional district. They are responsible for publishing a pollution prevention, control, and restoration plan within one year of enactment. The Management Conference for the Coeur d'Alene Basin must publish a water pollution prevention, control, and restoration plan within one year of enactment, clarifying responsibilities and suggesting a timetable for actions. The Plan developed under this section will clarify duties for water pollution prevention, suggest timetables for adoption, describe funding methods, and sources for programs and projects. The Plan will include strategies for water pollution prevention and control in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, funding methods, and incorporate environmental management concepts from State and Federal plans. The Plan will incorporate environmental management concepts from State and Federal plans and include a strategy for water pollution prevention and control in the Coeur d'Alene Basin. The Plan will include strategies for pollution prevention and management in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, with provisions for public review and approval by the Administrator. The Management Conference will hold a public meeting in Idaho to hear comments on the draft plan. The Administrator will approve the Plan within 30 days if it meets the requirements. Once approved, the Plan will be considered an approved management program and comprehensive conservation plan. Upon approval of the Plan, it will be deemed an approved management program and comprehensive conservation plan. Grant assistance may be provided to water pollution control agencies. Upon approval of the Plan, it will be implemented. Grant assistance may be provided to water pollution control agencies for the development of the Plan. Grants are available for assisting in the development of a Plan, including research, surveys, studies, and technical work. The federal share of grants cannot exceed 70% of the development costs, with the condition that non-Federal sources provide the remaining share, which can include in-kind services. Grants for developing a Plan under this subsection cannot exceed 70% of the costs, with the condition that non-Federal sources provide the remaining share, which can include in-kind services. The Administrator may establish terms and conditions for grant administration. The term 'Coeur d'Alene Basin' refers to the watershed in northern Idaho. The Administrator may establish terms and conditions for grant administration in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, defined as the watershed in northern Idaho. This section does not affect the jurisdiction or powers of any US or State department, agency, or entity related to the Basin created by treaty or memorandum. Authorization is granted to the Environmental Protection Agency to receive necessary appropriations for fiscal years 1995-1999 to carry out the provisions of this section without affecting the jurisdiction or powers of any US or State department, agency, or entity related to the Coeur d'Alene Basin. Authorization is granted to the Environmental Protection Agency for federal program coordination without impacting the jurisdiction of other government entities. The United States Geological Survey of the Department of the Interior will enhance data collection in the Coeur d'Alene Basin in cooperation with universities, research institutions, and state agencies. The Secretary of the Interior will work with water resource divisions to develop an integrated geographic information system in the Coeur d'Alene Basin and convert partial recording sites to continuous monitoring stations with full gauging capabilities. The Secretary of the Interior will work with appropriate departments and agencies of the States of Idaho and Washington to develop an integrated geographic information system in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, convert partial recording sites to continuous monitoring stations with full gauging capabilities, and establish additional monitoring stations for data collection and monitoring. The Secretary of the Interior, in cooperation with the United States Fish and Wildlife Service, will establish continuous monitoring stations in the Coeur d'Alene Basin for data collection, including ground water mapping and water quality monitoring. The United States Fish and Wildlife Service, in cooperation with the Coeur d'Alene Fish and Wildlife Management Cooperative, will establish a fisheries resources restoration program in the Coeur d'Alene Basin. The Wildlife Management Cooperative and the Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference will establish a fisheries restoration program and conduct a wildlife species and habitat assessment survey in the Coeur d'Alene Basin. The Act requires conducting a wildlife species and habitat assessment survey in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, including a survey of threatened and endangered species. The Act mandates a survey of various species, including Federal threatened and endangered species, migratory nongame species, and migratory bird populations. The Director of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service is authorized to conduct activities related to surveying threatened and endangered species, species of special concern, migratory nongame species, and migratory bird populations in the Coeur d'Alene Basin. The Director of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service is authorized to conduct activities related to surveying migratory bird populations in the Coeur d'Alene Basin, including breeding, migrating, and wintering birds. This includes improving fishery resources' health, investigating their status, and sharing information with interested parties. The United States Fish and Wildlife Service is authorized to improve the health of fishery resources, conduct investigations on their status, disseminate information to interested parties, and periodically update a survey of fishery resources in the Coeur d'Alene Basin. Authorization of appropriations is provided for fiscal years 1995-1999. The United States Fish and Wildlife Service is authorized to conduct surveys of fishery resources in the Coeur d'Alene Basin and appropriate funds for fiscal years 1995-1999. SEC. 4. RESTORATION PLAN. The Secretary of the Interior, through the Bureau of Land Management, will cooperate with other trustees to develop a restoration plan for public lands in the Coeur d'Alene Basin to reduce human and environmental risks. The Secretary of the Interior, in cooperation with other trustees, will develop a restoration plan for public lands in the Coeur d'Alene Basin to reduce human and environmental risks. This includes creating a computerized inventory of abandoned mining sites and contaminated areas, detailing key contaminants and their concentrations. The plan includes creating an information system inventory of abandoned mining sites and contaminated areas in the Basin, detailing key contaminants and concentrations. It also involves cleaning up contaminated sites, restoring damaged natural resources, and implementing stream and river restoration plans. The plan involves evaluating and prioritizing cleanup of mining contaminated sites, restoring damaged natural resources, implementing stream and river restoration plans, and monitoring restored areas for effectiveness. The plan includes placement of wood debris, habitat structures, rocks, stabilization of banks, riparian plantings, monitoring of restored areas, development of a land management plan with other agencies, and integrated cooperation for environmental risk reduction. (6) Develop and implement a land management plan with other agencies to reduce human health and environmental risks in the Basin.
(7) Maintain an integrated geographical information system for cultural and ecological resources and restoration activities in the Basin.
(8) Collaborate with the Forest Service and Fish and Wildlife for coordinated management within the Basin. (8) Develop a computerized geographical information system for cultural and ecological resources, contaminated areas, and restoration activities in the Basin. Collaborate with various wildlife agencies to create habitat management plans and monitoring for wildlife management areas. The Idaho Department of Fish and Game, along with the Coeur d'Alene Indian tribe and other wildlife interests, collaborate to develop habitat management plans for the Basin's streams, rivers, lakes, and wetlands. This includes creating cooperative wildlife management areas and monitoring their effectiveness. They also work with various agencies and organizations to manage public recreation in the area. (9) Monitor wildlife management areas in the Basin for effectiveness of improvements and restoration activities;
(10) Collaborate with various agencies to develop an integrated public recreation management plan for the Basin;
(11) Implement a lake and river information program for public use and health risk information. The Coeur d'Alene Indian tribe and public recreation interests collaborate to develop a public recreation management plan for the Basin, including a lake and river information program to provide health risk information. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to carry out activities related to these purposes. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to carry out activities related to data collection, inventory of mining waste source areas, contaminated lands, data management of resource information, restoration activities, and acquiring mining contaminated lands. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to carry out activities related to data collection, inventory of mining waste source areas, contaminated lands, data management, restoration activities, acquiring mining contaminated lands, design, engineering, construction, maintenance of restoration projects, and management facilities. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to carry out activities related to data collection, inventory of mining waste source areas, contaminated lands, restoration projects, management facilities, repositories for mine waste, lake and river information programs, recreation use supervision, and long-term restoration and land management plans. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to appropriate funds for restoration activities, lake and river information programs, recreation use supervision, and long-term maintenance of restored public lands for fiscal years 1995-2002. SEC. 5. EXEMPTION FROM CERCLA LIABILITY. The EPA and DOI are exempt from liability under CERCLA for actions taken under this Act.
